Mr Jimi Wanjigi is right. The Kenyan political scene needs fresh blood devoid of ethnic kingpins; individuals with fresh ideas for our country.  For far too long, we have had the same faces dominating the national stage but we witness little or no change.  We are still plagued with massive graft in government, ethnicity, joblessness and insufficient social amenities like healthcare, schools, water and education, among others. Help us serve you better by completing our quick survey. Further, with every regime consisting these same old folks, we keep witnessing blatant violation of basic human rights.  Kanu insists One Kenya cannot ignore Raila in 2022 game plan  Attention shifts to hardliners as parties seek to build alliances ahead of 2022 polls  Ruto's dilemma: Make UDA a big political tent or go for coalitions  Shaky mountain: How directionless Central has been exposed Right now, the same old politicians are luring us with theoretical economic models among other campaign propaganda.  In my view, the youth are better placed to take the mantle of Kenyan politics. Fresh political blood will divorce us from negative ethnicity, hatred and violence that has dominated politics.  Innocent Kefe is a Communication Strategist   Exploring the preparedness and the key timeliness of the IEBC to conduct the 2022 General Elections  Uhuru succession plan: Ruto's allies lose house committee slots as ODM loyalists take over positions  Uhuru's promise to Moi | Press Review By Wilson Sossion | 11 hours ago By Editorial | 11 hours ago By Mwangi Ngamate  | 11 hours ago By Solofo Randrianja  | 11 hours ago